@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Intro "Introduction"
@NEXT Install
@PREV Main

                     @{b}@{u}FOR WHAT DO I NEED cdxNetLaunch ?@{ub}@{uu}

 At  first: You need @{"AmiTCP/IP V4.1" LINK Info_AmiTCP} or higher and a @{"sana2.device" LINK Info_Sana2} (network
device) to use this program.
 If you don't have these already installed, it won't make sense to talk any
further ;-), so go for these programs immediately.

 On  the  other  hand,  if you already know AmiTCP/IP, you surely know that
each  time  you want to play around with the internet, you have to start it
by  executing  the "startnet" script.  Moreover, if you want to go offline,
you have to use the "offline" program etc.
 There  are  -  of  course - thousands of programs which will give you nice
buttons which will start these programs for you, @{i}but that is not enough @{ui}!

 I  think,  that  AmiTCP should start automatically if you are going to use
any  program  that  needs  it.   Additionally,  I think that it isn't worth
paying  the  phone  bill  when  a program doesn't really need your computer
being connected to another one.  I think, that the program should go online
if it needs to do so and go offline afterwards when it has done its job.
 Unfortunately, AmiTCP/IP doesn't offer such features.

 Here is where cdxNetLaunch comes into effect.

 * It will automatically start/stop AmiTCP and go on-/offline for you !
 * No more "startnet" !
 * Go offline after transmission is been done !
 @{b}* Widely configurable to fit the strangest needs !!!!!!!@{ub}

 @{"If you would like that, continue installing cdxNetLaunch !" LINK Install}

                                 @{b}@{u}EXAMPLE:@{ub}@{uu}

 Well,  it  seems  you  didn't  understood  what  I meant.  Okay, here's an
example:

 Imagine that you want to use "mftp" ©1995-96 Michael Neuweiler.

 @{u}Normal procedure:                   with cdxNetLaunch:                    @{uu}
                                     |
 open CLI & type startnet or         | --
 click on any button which will      |
 execute "startnet".                 |
                                     |
 AmiTCP is ready AND you're online   | --
 although this isn't neccessary for  |
 now !                               |
                                     |
 you start mftp                      | you start mftp
                                     | * AmiTCP will be loaded automatically.
                                     |   You won't go online.
                                     |
 you start a transmission            | You start a transmission
                                     | * cdxNetLaunch goes online for you
                                     |   (if the remote it isn't a local host)
                                     |
 your transmission is done           | your transmission is done.
 * you're staying online             | * after a certain time (definable)
                                     |   cdxNetLaunch notes that there isn't
                                     |   any reason to stay online anymore
                                     |   and goes offline for you.
                                     |
 your are hungry and go into the     | you are hungry and go into the
 kitchen                             | kitchen
                                     |
 you come back after 1 hour          | you come back after 2 hours
                                     |
 you see that you're still online    | you see that you aren't online
 and think of the phone bill...      | anymore.
                                     | * "all right", you think
                                     |
 you start another transmission      | you start another transmission
                                     | * cdxNetLaunch goes online for you
                                     |
 you end your transmission and       | you end your transmission and
 terminate mftp                      | terminate mftp
 * you're still online !             | * cdxNetLaunch goes offline and
                                     |   closes AmiTCP.
                                     |
 You stop AmiTCP.                    | --
 * You are offline.                  |
                                     |

 All  right  ?  Of course you can define every action cdxNetLaunch does for
you, you can disable parts of its functions and lots of stuff !

 Okay, let's have a look at the @{"Installation" LINK Install} chapter !
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Reqs "Requirements"
@NEXT Install
@PREV Intro

                               @{b}@{u}REQUIREMENTS:@{ub}@{uu}

 First  of all,  @{b}you have to@{ub} install @{"AmiTCP/IP" LINK Info_AmiTCP}.  If you haven't done that,
yet, please do it now !
 It is very important that AmiTCP is @{b}correctly@{ub} installed.  Please even note
that configurating cdxNetLaunch expects you to know several details of your
configuration  of  AmiTCP  and  your  sana2 device.  Therefore please first
install AmiTCP and your sana2 device and then we can continue to talk ;^)

 @{u}Requirements:@{uu}

 cdxNetLaunch needs @{b}Kickstart V37 (2.04)@{ub} or higher to run.
 cdxNetLaunch needs the following Amiga libraries:
   - utility.library
   - asl.library
   - amigaguide.library
   - icon.library
   - commodity.library
 and these public domain libraries (included in the archive):
   - @{"gadtoolsbox.library" LINK Duty}
   - @{"nofrag.library" LINK Duty}
 @{b}they'll be installed automatically by using the installation script !@{ub}

 These will be used if found (included in the archive):
   - @{"reqtools.library" LINK Duty}

 The "Installer" program is neccessary to use the @{"installation" LINK Install} script.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Install "Installation"
@NEXT ConfigMainWin
@PREV Reqs

                               @{b}@{u}INSTALLATION:@{ub}@{uu}

 Well, cdxNetLaunch can easily be installed using the installation script.
 There's only one important note:
 During  the  installation process - if you selected @{i}expert user@{ui} - you will
be   asked  whether  you  want  a  @{b}manual@{ub} or a @{b}automatic@{ub}  configuration  of
cdxNetLaunch.  Since the automatic configuration program is far better than
configurating cdxNetLaunch by yourself, you are recommended to try that one
first.
 If  you  start  cdxNetLaunch  a  first  time,  it will try to get a proper
@{"configuration for your system" LINK ConfigMainWin} and everything will be right.
 However, if  you  are using a @{"non-standard AmiTCP/IP configuration" LINK ConfigmanualInfo} or are
still    using    an    @{"old-styled   setup" LINK ConfigProblems},    you    should    use    the
@{"manual configuration option"  LINK Configmanual} !

                  @{fg shine}However, use the installation script !@{fg text}

 It  will install cdxNetLaunch to your system.  Then, when you start it the
first  time,  it will automatically say that no configuration is been found
and will allow you to start the @{"configuration program" LINK ConfigMainWin}.

 Please read the @{"configuration chapter" LINK ConfigMainWin} if you want to know something about
how  to  configurate  cdxNetLaunch.   You  may  also  use  the help buttons
provided on each (major) requester you might faced to.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ConfigMainWin "How to configurate cdxNetLaunch"
@TOC Main
@NEXT Usage
@PREV Install

                        @{b}@{u}CONFIGURING cdxNetLaunch:@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}@{fg shine}
               Please read this page even if you don't like
                             reading guides !
@{ub}@{fg text}
 This  page  will  explain  how  to  use  the  @{b}automatic  configuration@{ub}  of
cdxNetLaunch  which  will  automatically start if you start up cdxNetLaunch
the first  time,  as long as you didn't choose @{"manual configuration" LINK ConfigManual} during
the @{"installation process" LINK Install}.

 If  you  have  any @{"problems" LINK ConfigProblems}  with  this  program  (e.g.   it says "please
re-install  AmiTCP/IP"  or stuff), please refer to the @{"manual configuration" LINK ConfigManual}
page of cdxNetLaunch.

                         @{u}Automatic configuration:@{uu}

 Well, cdxNetLaunch of course needs some very special information about you
system: It needs to know which @{"sana2.device" LINK Info_Sana2} you use to go online and which
serial.device is used to contact the modem/network adapter.

 The  configuration  program  will  generate  some @{"scripts"  LINK Scripts}  that  will be
executed in order to go on-/offline or to start/stop AmiTCP.  These scripts
will be generated mainly from your startnet script.
 Therefore  this  requester will always appear if you changed your startnet
script   (this   option  is  not  available  if  you  are  using  a  manual
configuration !).

 In that case, if you didn't changed your interface nor your serial.device,
just click at okay to let the configuration program copy your changes.

  All these things will be requested by the main configuration window:

             +-+------------------------------------------+--+
             |·| cdxNetLaunch: Configuration              |  |
             +-+------------------------------------------+--+
             |                                               |
             | Your modem configuration:                     |
             |                                               |
             | @{fg shine}Modem interface@{fg text}: [................] [@{fg shine}@{"Change" LINK ConfigIFaceWin}@{fg text}] |
             |   @{fg shine}Serial device@{fg text}: [.............][.] [@{fg shine}@{"Change" LINK ConfigSerWin}@{fg text}] |
             | @{fg shine}AmiTCP/IP DOS-device@{fg text}: [...........]           |
             |                                               |
             | --------------------------------------------- |
             |                                               |
             |      [ @{fg shine}Okay@{fg text} ] [ @{fg shine}Undo@{fg text} ] [ @{fg shine}Help@{fg text} ] [@{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}]      |
             |                                               |
             +-----------------------------------------------+
@{b}
Before  you  continue,  please check the entries @{fg shine}Modem interface@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Serial
device@{fg text}.  These fields are very important for cdxNetLaunch:
@{ub}
 @{fg shine}Modem interface:@{fg text}
               Here you should read the name of your @{u}modem interface@{uu}.  This
               is  the  interface  which  describes  your @{"sana2.device" LINK Info_Sana2}  to
               AmiTCP/IP,  such  as  the @{"ppp.device" LINK Info_ppp}  or the rcslip.device.
               This  device  is  meant  to  @{i}control@{ui}  your  modem,  e.g.  it
               establishes a connection to your service provider.
               cdxNetLaunch  will enter here the interface it found in your
               startnet  script,  but  you  have  to  change  this  if your
               startnet script doesn't go online automatically.  If it does
               so, you can leave the entry as it is.
               @{b}To  change  this  value,  click at the @{"change" LINK ConfigIFaceWin} button to the
               right hand side !@{ub}
 @{fg shine}Serial device:@{fg text}
               This  field  says  which  serial.device your sana2.device is
               using  to  @{i}access@{ui}  your  modem.   The difference is that the
               sana2.device  is  the  software  used  to  @{i}talk@{ui}  to  another
               computer and the serial.device is the interface dealing with
               your @{i}hardware@{ui} itself.
               Please  check  the  name  and  the unit.  In most cases, the
               default "DEVS:serial.device" with unit 0 will work until you
               have  a  better  serial.device  or  a  multiserial card etc.
               You'd know about such things then, I guess.
               @{b}To  change  this  value,  click at the @{"change" LINK ConfigSerWin} button to the
               right hand side !@{ub}

The   field   @{fg shine}AmiTCP/IP  DOS-device@{fg text}  just  says  which  DOS  assign  you've
configurated  for AmiTCP.  Since cdxNetLaunch finds that out by itself, you
may just be happy that it is correct or contact the @{"author" LINK TalkLine} if not...;-)

 @{fg shine}Undo:@{fg text}         Restore your old values (if some).

 @{fg shine}Help:@{fg text}         This page

 @{fg shine}Okay:@{fg text}         Accept the new values.
               Please  note that the configuration utility will verify your
               data  (this  is  neccessary,  if  you'd  changed your AmiTCP
               configuration and cdxNetLaunch needs to be re-configurated).
               Therefore,  some  errors  might  occur.   I  hope stuff will
               explain itself, then.

 @{fg shine}Cancel:@{fg text}       Cancel, if possible ;-)

 @{fg shine}CLOSE GADGET:@{fg text} Same as @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}.
               If@{fg shine} cancel@{fg text} isn't available (because cdxNetLaunch doesn't have
               a  proper  configuration),  you can select this to abort the
               configuration  process (the @{fg shine}cancel@{fg text} gadget would be disabled,
               then).
               However,  if  you  close  the  window  and  cancelling isn't
               available you abort cdxNetLaunch !
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ConfigIFaceWin "Select you modem interface..."
@NEXT ConfigSerWin
@PREV ConfigMainWin
@TOC ConfigMainWin

                @{b}@{u}SELECTING A MODEM INTERFACE (sana2.device):@{ub}@{uu}

 Using  this  requester  you  can  select  the @{"sana2.device" LINK Info_Sana2} interface (see
appropiate chapters in the @{"AmiTCP/IP documentation" LINK AmiTCP:help/AmiTCP.guide/db-Interfaces}) which you are using to
control your modem.
 The list  will  automatically  be generated from the @{"AmiTCP:db/interfaces" LINK AmiTCP:db/interfaces/Main}
list of AmiTCP.


            +-+--------------------------------------------+--+
            | | cdxNetLaunch: Modem interface ...          |  |
            +-+--------------------------------------------+--+
            |                                                 |
            | Select you modem interface (sana2.device)       |
            |                                                 |
            |                   @{fg shine}Interfaces@{fg text}:                   |
            |  +-----------------------------------------+-+  |
            |  |                                         |#|  |
            |  |  List of interfaces...                  |#|  |
            |  |                                         |#|  |
            |  |                                         | |  |
            |  |                                         | |  |
            |  |                                         | |  |
            |  |                                         +-+  |
            |  |                                         |^|  |
            |  |                                         +-+  |
            |  |                                         |v|  |
            |  +-----------------------------------------+-+  |
            |                                                 |
            |   @{fg shine}Device@{fg text}: [.....................] @{fg shine}Unit@{fg text}: [...]   |
            |                                                 |
            | ----------------------------------------------- |
            |                                                 |
            |   [  @{fg shine}Okay@{fg text}  ] [  @{fg shine}Undo@{fg text}  ] [  @{fg shine}Help@{fg text}  ] [ @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text} ]   |
            |                                                 |
            +-------------------------------------------------+

 @{fg shine}Interfaces:@{fg text}
               Please  select  the  interface to your modem from this list.
               Double-Click to select & leave requester.
               The  @{fg shine}Device@{fg text}  information will tell you which software device
               and which @{fg shine}Unit@{fg text} of this the interface corresponds to.
               @{i}NOTE:  This list will automatically be updated if you change
               your   AmiTCP:db/interfaces  file  while  the  configuration
               program is running.
               This  means  that  you might add interfaces to the interface
               file in order to make them available to cdxNetLaunch...@{ui}

 @{fg shine}Okay:@{fg text}         Accept the new values.

 @{fg shine}Undo:@{fg text}         Restore your old values (if some).

 @{fg shine}Help:@{fg text}         This page

 @{fg shine}Cancel:@{fg text}       Cancel ;-)

 @{fg shine}CLOSE GADGET:@{fg text} Same as @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ConfigSerWin "Select your serial.device..."
@NEXT ConfigMainWin
@PREV ConfigIFaceWin
@TOC ConfigMainWin

                    @{b}@{u}SELECTING A SERIAL.DEVICE AND UNIT:@{ub}@{uu}

 Use  the  following  requester to select your serial.device which controls
your  modem  hardware.
 Please  note  that  the  @{i}full  path@{ui}  of  the serial.device is required for
cdxNetLaunch !
 You  may  not  need  this  requester  if  you  are  using a standard Amiga
configuration.

 These information is mainly used to determine whether you are online.
 You may disable this feature by using the
    Preferences/Configuration/No online checks
 menu entry from the @{"main window" LINK UseCmdWin}.

            +-+--------------------------------------------+--+
            | | cdxNetLaunch: Modem serial device          |  |
            +-+--------------------------------------------+--+
            |                                                 |
            | Your configuration:                             |
            |                                                 |
            |  @{fg shine}Serial device@{fg text}: [DEVS:serial.device....] [@{fg shine}Get@{fg text}]  |
            |           @{fg shine}Unit@{fg text}: [0..]                [@{fg shine}Default@{fg text}]  |
            |                                                 |
            | ----------------------------------------------- |
            |                                                 |
            |   [  @{fg shine}Okay@{fg text}  ] [  @{fg shine}Undo@{fg text}  ] [  @{fg shine}Help@{fg text}  ] [ @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text} ]   |
            |                                                 |
            +-------------------------------------------------+

 @{fg shine}Serial device:@{fg text}
               The path and filename of your serial.device.
               Use the @{fg shine}get@{fg text} button to open a file-requester.
 @{fg shine}Unit:@{fg text}
               Unit of serial.device to check.
 @{fg shine}Default:@{fg text}
               Sets @{fg shine}serial device@{fg text} to "DEVS:serial.device" and @{fg shine}unit@{fg text} to 0.

 @{fg shine}Okay:@{fg text}         Accept the new values.

 @{fg shine}Undo:@{fg text}         Restore your old values (if some).

 @{fg shine}Help:@{fg text}         This page

 @{fg shine}Cancel:@{fg text}       Cancel ;-)

 @{fg shine}CLOSE GADGET:@{fg text} Same as @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ConfigProblems "What problems may appear using the automatic configuration ?"
@TOC ConfigMainWin
@PREV ConfigManualInfo

                       @{b}@{u}AUTO-CONFIGURATION PROBLEMS:@{ub}@{uu}

                          @{b}Problems with startnet:@{ub}

 The  auto-configuration  doesn't work with all AmiTCP/IP configurations as
reported from some nice people (thanks for your notes !).
 The  main  reason  for imporper work of the auto-configuration is that the
@{"AmiTCP:bin/startnet" LINK AmiTCP:bin/startnet/main} script  doesn't  seem  to be a standard AmiTCP/IP 4.1+
startnet script.  In detail, configurating an AmiTCP interface (i.e.  going
online) using the programs
 AmiTCP:bin/ifconfig, AmiTCP:bin/online etc.
is not  supported  but @{"AmiTCP:bin/bootpconfig" LINK AmiTCP:help/Amitcp.guide/bootpconfig} which I guess is recommended
by the AmiTCP/IP developpers.
 @{"Click here for a so I call standard startnet file." LINK Startnet}

 @{b}These error messages indicate such a case:@{ub}

 @{u}If the line ".def IFACE @{i}<iface>@{ui}" is not been found:@{uu}

 | cdxNetLaunch configuration error:
 | Can't find a interface definition in
 | the startnet file AmiTCP:bin/startnet.
 | Please re-install AmiTCP/IP.

 @{u}If the line "AmiTCP:bin/bootpconfig ..." is not been found:@{uu}

 | cdxNetLaunch configuration error:
 | Sorry, no "bootpconfig" call found.
 | That means that you don't configure any
 | sana2.device when running your startnet
 | script.
 | Please re-install AmiTCP saying that you
 | want you modem interface to be started
 | when you run startnet.
 | This program will make sure that this
 | won't happen, then.

 @{u}If the line "FailAt 21" is not been found:@{uu}

 | cdxNetLaunch configuration error:
 | Sorry, no "FailAt 21" call found.
 | It seems that your startnet script is
 | not the one I expect it to be !
 | Please re-install AmiTCP !!!!

 In  that  case,  if  you don't want to change your current configuration I
suggest it would be great for you to @{"manually configurate" LINK ConfigManual} cdxNetLaunch.


                    @{b}Problems with AmiTCP:db/interfaces:@{ub}

 Additionally, cdxNetLaunch expects to find @{i}at least one @{ui}valid @{"sana2.device" LINK Info_Sana2}
@{"interface description" LINK AmiTCP:help/AmiTCP.guide/db-interfaces} in @{"your AmiTCP:db/interfaces" LINK AmiTCP:db/interfaces/Main} file (see @{"copy of mine" LINK Interfaces}).
 @{i}Valid @{ui}in  that  case means the a device described by a name (e.g.  "ppp0")
does  also logically exists as a file on your system (in the latter example
DEVS:networks/@{"ppp.device" LINK Info_ppp}).
 Since  you  should  already  have  such  a device ready I suggest adding a
relating  line  to  that  file  should be easy (since even AmiTCP/IP itself
needs that entry to work).

 @{u}However, cdxNetLaunch configuration will claim if no device is found:@{uu}

 | cdxNetLaunch configuration error:
 | Can't load list of AmiTCP interfaces
 | from 'AmiTCP:db/interfaces' !
 | Going to quit...


                    @{b}Further problems with cdxNetLaunch:@{ub}

 Some  even  reported that cdxNetLaunch @{i}crashes @{ui}:( if they tried to use the
preferences windows reachable via the main window's menus.
 I  hope  that  I  now fixed that problem (the sub-processes used a routine
that  performed SAS/C stack-checking what is not very good if you are using
another process ;-)

 Anyhow, if you are faced to such fx, please @{"e-mail me" LINK TalkLine} !

@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ConfigManualInfo "What means » manual configuration « ?"
@TOC ConfigManual
@NEXT ConfigManualLimits
@PREV ConfigManual

          @{b}@{u}COMPARATON BETWEEN MANUAL AND AUTOMATIC CONFIGURATION:@{ub}@{uu}

 Well,  the main difference between a @{b}manual@{ub} and an @{b}automatic@{ub} configuration
is  that  the  automatic  configuration  program will create a @{i}new@{ui} startnet
script  (and  of course online, offline and stopnet scripts) in contrast to
the  manual  configuration  which  will simply make use of already existent
scripts.
  Note  that in future (next release, I hope) both methods will be convered
by the configuration program; for now manual configuration is only possible
by using the @{"installation script" LINK Install}.

 Do  you want to see how the scripts created by the automatic configuration
program look like (using the @{"ppp.device" LINK Info_ppp}) ?

See: @{" scripts/Startnet.bat " LINK startnet.bat}
     @{" scripts/Stopnet.bat  " LINK stopnet.bat}
     @{" scripts/Online.bat   " LINK online.bat}
     @{" scripts/Offline.bat  " LINK offline.bat}

 Moreover,  some  features  offered  to you by cdxNetLaunch won't cooperate
with a manual configuration (@{"which ?" LINK ConfigManualLimits}).


 Another difference depends on the configuration program used to perform an
automatic  configuration:   It  will set several tooltypes for you; using a
manual configuration these tooltypes will be set by the installer script.
 Refer  to  the  @{"tooltype explanation" LINK ToolTypes} in order to find out which tooltypes
will be affected by the installer script.

 See the configuration pages for more information:
  @{" Automatic configuration          " LINK ConfigMainWin}
  @{" Manual configuration             " LINK ConfigManual}
  @{" Problems with auto-configuration " LINK ConfigProblems}

@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ConfigManualLimits "What features doesn't work with a manual configuration ?"
@TOC ConfigManual
@NEXT ConfigManual
@PREV ConfigManualInfo

          @{b}@{u}LIMITS TO cdxNetLaunch BECAUSE OF MANUAL CONFIGURATION:@{ub}@{uu}

 The  following features will either not work or cause ugly side-effects if
you  are  using  them  while cdxNetLaunch had been manually configurated by
you (@{"menu items" LINK UseCmdWin} in [brackets]):

 a) Using the configuration program:
    [Preferences/Configuration/Configuration]

    That  is  not possible since it expects your AmiTCP:bin/startnet script
    to have a @{"certain structure" LINK ConfigProblems}.

 b) Automatically note changes to the startnet file:
    [Preferences/Configuration/Supervise startnet]

    Normally,  cdxNetLaunch would note if you change your startnet file and
    would open the auto-configuration program, then.
    That  is  again  not  possible  here  (you  may  don't  need  it  since
    cdxNetLaunch  will @{"execute right that script" LINK ConfigManual} if you are using a manual
    configuration).

 c) Automatically note changes to the startnet file when starting:
    [Preferences/Configuration/Check dates on startup]

    Normally, cdxNetLaunch would compare the dates of @{"its scripts" LINK scripts} (created
    by  the  auto-configuration program) to the startnet file creation date
    and   will   -   if   the   startnet   is   "younger"   -  execute  the
    @{"auto-configuration program" LINK ConfigMainWin}.

 Since  the  mentioned  features  are  all build to ensure that the scripts
created  by  cdxNetLaunch  are  up  to  date (i.e.  running the same actual
interface etc.) and a manual configuration however expects you to have your
own  scripts,  it's simply that the job keeping these scripts up to date is
upon you.
 There are no other restrictions to the functionality of cdxNetLaunch.

@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Startnet "My startnet file"
@{fg shine}
The important lines for the auto-configuration program are marked @{b}bold@{ub}.
Click here for the @{"stopnet file" LINK StopNet}.
@{fg text}
.key IP,HN/K,DEST/K,MASK/K,GW/K,USER/K,SRV/S,BOOTP/S,UMASK/K,S2CF/K,S2OPT/K,IFACE/K,DEBUG/S
.bra {
.ket }
;
; AmiTCP/IP startnet script
;
; Copyright © 1994 AmiTCP/IP Group,
;                  NSDi - Network Solutions Development Inc., Finland
;                  All rights reserved.
;
; *NOTE*  NORMALLY YOU SHOULD USE THE PROVIDED CONFIGURATION UTILITY
; *NOTE*  TO CHANGE THE CONFIGURATION.  IF YOU NEED TO CHANGE THE 
; *NOTE*  CONFIGURATION MANUALLY, RESTRICT ANY MODIFICATIONS TO THIS 
; *NOTE*  "DEF" SECTION.
;
; IP address if known, _nothing_ otherwise
.def IP    
; Our full host name and aliases if known, _nothing_ otherwise
; (if this is set, the IP _must_ be set, too)
.def HN    
; The destination address, needed only if GW is not good destination
.def DEST  
; netmask if known, _nothing_ otherwise
.def MASK  
; IP address of the default gateway if known, _nothing_ otherwise
.def GW    
; Default login name
.def USER  codex
; User's file creation mask
.def UMASK 022
; "SRV" if servers are used, _nothing_ otherwise
.def SRV   
; "BOOTP" if bootstrap protocol is used, _nothing_ otherwise
.def BOOTP 
; Interface name
@{b}.def IFACE ppp0@{ub}
; Sana-II device configuration file, _nothing_ otherwise
.def S2CF  ppp0.config
; Sana-II device configuration to be stored into the configuration file
.def S2OPT "serial.device 0 19600 0.0.0.0 MTU=1500 DIALSCRIPT=CODER:NetWork/usrdata/codex/Dialscript.txt CD 7WIRE "
;
; *NOTE*  YOU SHOULD NOT NEED TO EDIT ANYTHING BELOW. IF YOU NEED TO ADD
; *NOTE*  CONFIGURATIONS OF ADDITIONAL INTERFACES OR TO START UTILITIES,
; *NOTE*  DO IT IN THE AmiTCP:db/User-Startnet.
;
; Set the failat level so that the errors can be handled by the script
@{b}FailAt 21@{ub}
; Log in
echo
echo login: {USER}
AmiTCP:bin/login -f {USER}
AmiTCP:bin/umask {UMASK}
run AmiTCP:AmiTCP {DEBUG}
WaitForPort AMITCP
If NOT Warn
  ; Create Sana2 configuration file if used
  If NOT X EQ "X{S2CF}"
    ; Assure that ENV:Sana2 exists
    If NOT Exists ENV:Sana2
      MakeDir ENV:Sana2
    EndIf
    ; Create configuration file
    Echo "{S2OPT}" >ENV:Sana2/{S2CF}
  EndIf
  ; Do we need loopback?
  If X EQ "X{SRV}"
    Set LOOPBACK=""
  Else
    Set LOOPBACK="LOOPBACK"
  EndIf
  ; Configure interface
@{b}  AmiTCP:bin/bootpconfig {IFACE} IP {IP$*} DEST {DEST$*} MASK {MASK$*} GW {GW$*} $LOOPBACK {BOOTP} {DEBUG}@{ub}
  If NOT Warn
    If NOT X EQ "X{HN}"
      rx "address AMITCP; 'ADD HOST {IP} {HN}'"
    Else
      If NOT X EQ "X{DEBUG}"
        echo "Quering Name Server for the host name..."
      EndIf
    EndIf
    setenv HOSTNAME `AmiTCP:bin/hostname`
    Assign TCP: Exists >NIL:
    IF Warn
@{b}      Mount TCP: from AmiTCP:devs/Inet-Mountlist@{ub}
    EndIf
    ; Start the internet `super server' if wanted
    If NOT X EQ "X{SRV}"
      If X EQ "X{DEBUG}"
        Run <NIL: >NIL: AmiTCP:bin/inetd
      Else
        Run AmiTCP:bin/inetd {DEBUG}
      EndIf
    EndIf
    ;
    ; Configure any additional interfaces & start utilities in 
    ; AmiTCP:db/User-Startnet
    ;
    If Exists AmiTCP:db/User-Startnet
      Execute AmiTCP:db/User-Startnet
    EndIf
  Else
    Echo Interface {IFACE} configuration failed!
    Echo Stopping AmiTCP
    AmiTCP:bin/stopnet FLUSH
  EndIf
Else
  Echo AmiTCP couldn't be started!
EndIf

; EOF
@ENDNODE

@NODE StopNet "My stopnet script"
@PREV StartNet
@NEXT StartNet
@{fg shine}
The important lines for the auto-configuration program are marked @{b}bold@{ub}.
@{fg text}
.KEY FLUSH/S
.BRA {
.KET }

; $Id: stopnet,v 3.1 1994/05/27 07:08:39 jraja Exp $

rx "address AMITCP; KILL" ; Send "KILL" to AmiTCP

If {FLUSH}
	Wait 2 secs
	If `rx "Say Show(ports, AMITCP)"` EQ 0
		Avail >NIL: FLUSH
	EndIf
EndIf

@{b}offline ppp0@{ub}

; EOF
@ENDNODE

@NODE Interfaces "AmiTCP:db/interfaces
#
#	$Id: interfaces,v 4.12 1995/01/16 23:29:58 ppessi Exp $
#
#	Network interface configuration for the AmiTCP/IP
#
#	Copyright © 1994 AmiTCP/IP Group,
#	                 Network Solutions Development Inc.
#	                 All rights reserved.
#
# AmiTCP/IP uses the network interface to communicate with SANA-II devices,
# just like DOS uses handlers or filesystems to communicate with exec
# devices.  A network interface is created and configured with `ifconfig'
# utility.  AmiTCP/IP can create several network interfaces for each SANA-II
# device; this is seldom useful, except when two different IP addresses are
# needed for one host or when network has several different framings for IP
# or (for example, ARP has got two different framings for IP).
#
# The Install_AmiTCP installation script depends on the interface
# names defined here, so do not change them.
#
# There is a built-in interface "lo0" in AmiTCP/IP, other interfaces should
# be defined here.
#
# This configuration file is read with template:
# NAME/A, DEV=DEVICE/A/K, UNIT/N/A/K, IPTYPE/N/K, ADDR=ADDRESS/K,
# ARPTYPE=IPARPTYPE/N/K, IPREQ=IPREQUESTS/N/K, ARPREQ=ARPREQUESTS/N/K,
# WRITEREQ=WRITEREQUESTS/N/K, NOTRACKING/S, NOQUICKIO/S, FILTER/S, NOARP/S,
# P2P=POINT2POINT/S, NOSIMPLEX/S, LOOPBACK/S
#
# Lines can be continued if their last character is '+'. The '#' and ';' are
# comment characters - rest of the line is ignored
#
# Parameters are interpreted as follows:
# NAME/A
#   New-style AmiTCP/IP network interface name. This name must be
#   unique. If you have multiple units for the same device, then you
#   must differentiate the units by adding the unit number as a suffix
#   to the name, for example. The maximum lenght for the name is 15
#   bytes.
# DEV=DEVICE/A/K
#   Sana-II (old-style AmiTCP/IP) device name
# UNIT/N/A/K
#   Sana-II (old-style AmiTCP/IP) device unit number
# ADDR=ADDRESS/K (*
#   Hardware address used by SANA-II device configuration in hexadecimal
#   notation with octets separated by colons,
#   e.g. 08:00:13:AE:45:EF. This should be used if your ethernet adapter
#   has no address ROM, for example.
# IPTYPE/N/K (*
#   Packet type (framing) for Internet Protocol (IP)
# IPREQ=IPREQUESTS/N/K
#   IO requests allocated for receiving IP packets.
# ARPTYPE=IPARPTYPE/N/K (*
#   Packet type (framing) for Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)
# ARPREQ=ARPREQUESTS/N/K
#   IO requests allocated for receiving ARP packets
# WRITEREQ=WRITEREQUESTS/N/K
#   IO requests allocated for transmitting packets
# NOTRACKING/S
#   Disable the packet type tracking on SANA-II devices.  This feature is
#   needed to circumvent a bug in a2060.device V37.2 
# NOQUICKIO/S/S
#   Prevent AmiTCP/IP from using Quick IO on SANA-II devices when writing to
#   network. This feature is needed to circumvent bugs in QuickNetS2.device
#   V1.36 and earlier.
# FILTER/S
#   Enable Sana-II packet filtering for this interface. This is needed only
#   if you have several protocol stacks using the same Sana-II device and
#   unit. E.g., Envoy uses IP, too, so the FILTERing should be enabled on
#   interfaces which are shared with Envoy
# NOARP/S
#   Disable the ARP for this interface
# P2P=POINT2POINT/S
#   Use the device as point-to-point device
# NOSIMPLEX/S
#   Disable the copying of broadcast packets.  Set this parameter if we hear
#   our own broadcasts
# LOOPBACK/S
#   Set this parameter if it is loopback
#
# *) Don't set these parameters if you don't know what you are doing.
#    AmiTCP/IP recognizes Ethernet, Arcnet (RFC 1051 framing), SLIP and PPP
#    drivers automatically.  See file <netinclude/net/sana2tags.h> for the
#    packet types used for these drivers.
# 
# Here are few examples:
#
# AmiPPP
amippp DEV=DEVS:networks/amippp.device UNIT=0 P2P IPTYPE=2048 IPREQ=16 WRITEREQ=16
# Serial Line IP
#
slip0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/rhslip.device UNIT=0
# IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
#
# SLIP with Van Jacobson header compression 
#
cslip0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/rhcslip.device UNIT=0
# IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
#
# PPP device by Holger Kruse
#
ppp0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/ppp.device UNIT=0 IPTYPE=33 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
#
# Ethernet adapter A2065
#
ether0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/a2065.device UNIT=0
a2065 DEV=DEVS:Networks/a2065.device UNIT=0
# IPTYPE=2048 ARPTYPE=2054 ARPREQ=4 IPREQ=16 WRITEREQ=16 
#
# AmeriStar A4066 Ethernet adapter
#
a4066 DEV=DEVS:Networks/a4066.device UNIT=0
#
# Hydra Ethernet adapter
#
hydra DEV=DEVS:Networks/hydra.device UNIT=0
#
# GoldenGate WD80xx Ethernet adapter
#
wd80xx DEV=DEVS:Networks/wd80xx.device UNIT=0
# NOTE: This needs an configuration file for the IRQ and MEM address settings!
#
# ASDG EB920 Ethernet adapter
#
eb920 DEV=DEVS:Networks/eb920.device UNIT=0
#
# Village Tronic Ariadne Ethernet adapter
#
ariadne DEV=DEVS:Networks/ariadne.device UNIT=0
#
# QuickNet Ethernet adapter
#
quicknet DEV=QuickNetS2.device UNIT=0 NOQUICKIO
#
# GoldenGate 2 Ethernet for 3COM 3c503 card
# NOTE: This needs an configuration file for the IRQ and ISA address settings!
#
gg_3c503 DEV=DEVS:Networks/gg_3c503.device UNIT=0
#
# GoldenGate 2 Ethernet for NE1000 card
# NOTE: This needs an configuration file for the IRQ and ISA address settings!
#
gg_ne1000 DEV=DEVS:Networks/gg_ne1000.device UNIT=0
#
# GoldenGate 2 Ethernet for NE2000 card
# NOTE: This needs an configuration file for the IRQ and ISA address settings!
#
gg_ne2000 DEV=DEVS:Networks/gg_ne2000.device UNIT=0
#
# GoldenGate 2 Ethernet for SMC/WD 80x3 card
# NOTE: This needs an configuration file for the IRQ, 
# IO and BASE address settings!
#
gg_smc DEV=DEVS:Networks/gg_smc.device UNIT=0
# 
# Arcnet adapter a2060 
#
arcnet0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/a2060.device UNIT=0 NOTRACKING 
a2060 DEV=DEVS:Networks/a2060.device UNIT=0 NOTRACKING 
# IPTYPE=240 ARPTYPE=241 ARPREQ=4 IPREQ=16 WRITEREQ=16 
#
# An X.25 driver by Dave Martin
#
ax25 DEV=DEVS:Networks/ax25.device UNIT=0 +
  IPTYPE=204 ARPTYPE=205 ARPREQ=3 IPREQ=16 WRITEREQ=16
#
# PLIP (Parallel Line IP)
#
plip0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/plip.device UNIT=0 +
  IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
plip1 DEV=DEVS:Networks/plip.device UNIT=1 +
  IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
#
# Liana (PLIP) interface
#
liana0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/liana.device UNIT=0 +
  IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
liana1 DEV=DEVS:Networks/liana.device UNIT=1 +
  IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
#
# Village Tronic Ariadne Liana (PLIP) interface
#
ariadneliana0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/ariadneliana.device UNIT=0 +
  IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
ariadneliana1 DEV=DEVS:Networks/ariadneliana.device UNIT=1 +
  IPTYPE=2048 NOARP P2P IPREQ=8 WRITEREQ=8
#
# EOF
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Startnet.bat "Startnet.bat - created by auto-configuration."
@{" Do you want to see the source (original) startnet script ?" LINK startnet}
@{" startnet.bat " LINK startnet.bat}@{" stopnet.bat " LINK stopnet.bat}@{" online.bat " LINK online.bat}@{" offline.bat " LINK offline.bat}
.key IP,HN/K,DEST/K,MASK/K,GW/K,USER/K,SRV/S,BOOTP/S,UMASK/K,S2CF/K,S2OPT/K,IFACE/K,DEBUG/S
.bra {
.ket }
.def IP    
.def HN    
.def DEST  
.def MASK  
.def GW    
.def USER  codex
.def UMASK 022
.def SRV   
.def BOOTP 
.def IFACE ppp0
.def S2CF  ppp0.config
.def S2OPT "serial.device 0 19600 0.0.0.0 MTU=1500 DIALSCRIPT=CODER:NetWork/usrdata/codex/Dialscript.txt CD 7WIRE "
FailAt 21
Path SYS:RexxC SYS:System SYS:Utilities SYS:Commodities AmiTCP: AmiTCP:bin ADD
echo
echo login: {USER}
AmiTCP:bin/login -f {USER}
AmiTCP:bin/umask {UMASK}
run AmiTCP:AmiTCP {DEBUG}
WaitForPort AMITCP
If NOT Warn
  If NOT X EQ "X{S2CF}"
    If NOT Exists ENV:Sana2
      MakeDir ENV:Sana2
    EndIf
    Echo "{S2OPT}" >ENV:Sana2/{S2CF}
  EndIf
  If X EQ "X{SRV}"
    Set LOOPBACK=""
  Else
    Set LOOPBACK="LOOPBACK"
  EndIf
  ; *** for use with cdxNetLaunch ***   AmiTCP:bin/bootpconfig {IFACE} IP {IP$*} DEST {DEST$*} MASK {MASK$*} GW {GW$*} $LOOPBACK {BOOTP} {DEBUG}
  If NOT Warn
    If NOT X EQ "X{HN}"
      rx "address AMITCP
    Else
      If NOT X EQ "X{DEBUG}"
        echo "Quering Name Server for the host name..."
      EndIf
    EndIf
    setenv HOSTNAME `AmiTCP:bin/hostname`
    Assign TCP: Exists >NIL:
    IF Warn
      Mount TCP: from AmiTCP:devs/Inet-Mountlist
    EndIf
    If NOT X EQ "X{SRV}"
      If X EQ "X{DEBUG}"
        Run <NIL: >NIL: AmiTCP:bin/inetd
      Else
        Run AmiTCP:bin/inetd {DEBUG}
      EndIf
    EndIf
    If Exists AmiTCP:db/User-Startnet
      Execute AmiTCP:db/User-Startnet
    EndIf
  Else
    Echo Interface {IFACE} configuration failed!
    Echo Stopping AmiTCP
    AmiTCP:bin/stopnet FLUSH
  EndIf
Else
  Echo AmiTCP couldn't be started!
EndIf


