@NODE ConfigManual "Manual configuration of cdxNetLaunch"
@TOC Main
@PREV ConfigProblems
@NEXT ConfigManualInfo

                          @{b}@{u}A CUSTOM CONFIGURATION@{ub}@{uu}

 @{u}Please note:@{uu}

 a) this   option  should  only  be  used  if  you   tried  the  @{"automatic" LINK Install}
    configuration and that one failed !
 b) In  future, the configuration program  will even be able to do a manual
    configuration thus all things described here may change in future.

 @{u}Some informations ahead ?@{uu}

 @{" Reasons why you should use a manual configuration." LINK ConfigProblems}
 @{" What is a custom configuration ?" LINK ConfigManualInfo}
 @{" Which features of cdxNetLaunch do not work with a manual configuration ?" LINK ConfigManualLimits}

                 @{b}What you need for a manual configuration:@{ub}

 a) You need to have four script files (batch files) that do the following:
    - start AmiTCP/IP but @{i}don't go online @{ui}!
    - stop AmiTCP/IP @{i}and @{ui}go offline.
    - go online
    - go offline
    The @{"automatic configuration" LINK ConfigMainWin} program would generate @{"these" LINK scripts} for you !
 b) You need to know:
    - The complete path of the above.
    - The @{"AmiTCP/IP interface name" LINK Amitcp:help/AmiTCP.guide/db-interfaces} of your @{"sana2.device" LINK Info_Sana2} (which goes online
      for you).
    - The real device file it is associated to (see @{"AmiTCP:db/interfaces" LINK Amitcp:db/interfaces/main}).
    - Its unit (normally 0).
    - The serial.device  you are using (which will be DEVS:serial.device in
      most cases).
    - Its unit (normally 0).
    - In  the case you changed the AmigaDOS TCP: device of  @{"inet" LINK amitcp:doc/inet-handler.doc/main}, that new
      name (normally TCP:).
    - All path names that are neccessary to execute the scripts above.

                 @{b}How to manually configurate cdxNetLaunch:@{ub}

 a) Start the installation script.
 b) Select @{i}expert user @{ui}at the beginning.
 c) After having selected the location of cdxNetLaunch and its data you are
    asked  whether  you  want  to  perform  a manual configuration - select
    "Manual".

 Now enter the data the script requests from you.
 Note  that the installation script won't write anything to your disk until
you  confirmed  all  data thus you can abort the script at any time, if you
wish.

                                 @{b}Test it:@{ub}

 Now,  start  cdxNetLaunch  to  test your configuration.  It shall react as
follows:
 a) When   starting,  the @{"main  window" LINK UseCmdWin}  shall  be opened (no configuration
    window !).
 b) If  you start any AmiTCP/IP application, say MFTP, the @{"new application" LINK UseAppWin}
    window should appear.
    After having used it, AmiTCP/IP should be loaded without going online.
    Then,  if  you  go to do any outer net-work, your modem should dial and
    AmiTCP/IP should go online.
 c) Quit  your  application.   If  you  didn't @{"disabled" LINK Prefs_Delay} cdxNetLaunch to go
    offline  and/or  stop  AmiTCP/IP, AmiTCP/IP should be unloaded and your
    modem should go offline.

                             @{b}Trouble-shooting:@{ub}

 Say it doesn't work.
 Here are some hints how to remove a bug:
 a) Use   the  menuitem  "Preferences/IO  Windows/Define  command IO..." to
    change  the  script output window.  Add the string "/CLOSE/WAIT" behind
    the  string.   Now,  you  have  to close the i/o window of your scripts
    before they'll disappear.  Then, you can read any error messages.
 b) Check  the  pathes  in  the @{"script files" LINK Scripts} generated by the installation
    script.
 c) Try to execute the @{"scripts" LINK Scripts} in the script directory by yourself.
 d) Try to add a STACK 12000 call to your scripts if the crash your machine.
 e) @{i}Write me an @{"e-mail" LINK TalkLine} explaining what goes wrong and I'll try to help.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE 

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Scripts "The scripts used by cdxNetLaunch"
@TOC ConfigMainWin

                           @{b}@{u}SOME SCRIPTS TO WORK:@{ub}@{uu}

 cdxNetLaunch will generate its own scripts to take appropiate actions.
 These  scripts  will be saved to PREFSDIR:scripts/#?.bat where PREFSDIR is
the preferences directory of cdxNetLaunch defined in its tooltypes.

 These scripts will be needed (and generated by the configuration program):

 @{"startnet.bat" LINK Startnet.bat} like AmiTCP:bin/startnet, but will not go online (that means
               it won't @{"bootpconfig" LINK AmiTCP:help/Amitcp.guide/bootpconfig} your modem interface).
 @{"stopnet.bat " LINK Stopnet.bat}  simply executes AmiTCP:bin/stopnet to stop AmiTCP.
               Will even go offline for you.
 @{"online.bat  " LINK Online.bat}   bootpconfigurates  your  modem interface, i.e.  it will tell
               AmiTCP that this interface is now ready to work.
 @{"offline.bat " LINK Offline.bat}  goes offline for you.

 When  these  scripts  are  executed,  a the i/o stream you defined will be
opened  and  the  script  output will be written there.  If you notice that
anything wents wrong at all, enter the I/O stream
   CON:0/0/400/100/title/AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE
                               ^^^ this will say that the window won't
                                   be closed until you clicked the close-
                                   gadget.
                                   Therefore you may read what went wrong.

 Please  note  that the line "Path SYS:RexxC AmiTCP:  SYS:System AmiTCP:bin
...ADD" will be added to the scripts by default.  If your pathes to AmiTCP:
or   ARexx   are   different,   please   edit   this   by   modifying   the
@{"INITCMD tooltype" LINK tooltypes}.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Usage "How to use cdxNetLaunch command/new application window"
@NEXT Prefs
@PREV ConfigMainWin
@TOC Main

                           @{b}@{u}INSTRUCTIONS OF USE:@{ub}@{uu}

 cdxNetLaunch  V1.0 has two important requesters which may appear.  Here is
the guide how to use them:

 The first one is the @{"command" LINK UseCmdWin} window. You can open it using the hotkey you
defined  in  the  tooltypes  of  cdxNetLaunch.   This  window allows you to
directly  command  cdxNetLaunch  to start/stop AmiTCP or to go off-/online.
Additionally,  you  can use it to change whether you want to quit AmiTCP if
it  is possible or whether you want to go offline if cdxNetLaunch finds out
that you could.
 Moreover, you can modify the @{"preferences" LINK Menu_Prefs} settings of cdxNetLaunch by using
the Preferences menu.

 The  @{"new application" LINK UseAppWin}  window  on the other hand appears when cdxNetLaunch
finds  a new application program that wants to use AmiTCP/IP.  Using it you
can  define  what  kind  of program that it and what you want to do if this
program  closes  its  line (whether you automatically want to go offline or
not).

 @{" Using the command window         " LINK UseCmdWin}
 @{" Using the new application window " LINK UseAppWin}

 @{" The preferences requesters       " LINK Prefs}

                               @{b}@{u}HOW TO QUIT:@{ub}@{uu}

 Open the @{"command" LINK UseCmdWin} window and select Quit from the project menu.
 Or start Exchange and remove cdxNetLaunch.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE UseCmdWin "Using the command window"
@TOC Usage
@NEXT UseAppWin

                            @{b}@{u}THE COMMAND WINDOW:@{ub}@{uu}

 You  can  open  this  @{i}command window @{ui}pressing the CX_HOTKEY defined in the
tooltypes  of cdxNetLaunch.  You may even use the Exchange program to "open
interface".
 It will look like:

                   +-+--------------------------+--+--+
                   | | cdxNetLaunch             |  |  |
                   +-+--------------------------+--+--+
                   |                                  |
                   |  [@{fg shine}Start AmiTCP@{fg text}]  [@{fg shine}Stop AmiTCP@{fg text} ]  |
                   |                                  |
                   |  [   @{fg shine}Online@{fg text}   ]  [  @{fg shine}Offline@{fg text}   ]  |
                   |                                  |
                   +----------------------------------+

                                 @{u}Gadgets:@{uu}

 @{fg shine}Start AmiTCP:@{fg text} This button will cause to start AmiTCP.

 @{fg shine}Stop AmiTCP:@{fg text}  This button might be used to stop AmiTCP.
               This  is  only  possible  if  no more applications are using
               AmiTCP/IP.

 @{fg shine}Online:@{fg text}       Use it to go online.
               This is of course only possible if AmiTCP/IP is been started
               before.

 @{fg shine}Offline:@{fg text}      Click here to go offline.
               Possible  only if AmiTCP/IP is active, you are online and no
               more applications need your machine to be online.

 @{fg shine}CLOSE GADGET:@{fg text} Will  "Hide"  the window, i.e.  it will close the window but
               not terminate cdxNetLaunch.

          @{b}Additionally, some menus are available in this window:@{ub}

                             @{u}The project menu:@{uu}

 @{fg shine}Documentation...:@{fg text}
               Loads this guide.
               If  cdxNetLaunch  isn't  able  to find this file, it opens a
               requester which you should use to locate it.

 @{fg shine}About...:@{fg text}     Just guess ;^)

 @{fg shine}Hide:@{fg text}         Will close the window; cdxNetLaunch will keep running.

 @{fg shine}Quit...:@{fg text}      @{i}Attempt@{ui} to quit cdxNetLaunch.
               There  are  several reasons why this could fail; the program
               will inform you about that.

                           @{u}The preferences menu:@{uu}

 @{fg shine}@{b}Automatic operations:@{ub}@{fg text}

     @{fg shine}@{"Adjust time delays...:" LINK Prefs_Delay}@{fg text}
               Opens  a  requester  which  allows  you  to  modify the time
               delays.   cdxNetLaunch  will  wait  a certain time before it
               stops AmiTCP or goes offline.
     @{fg shine}Never close AmiTCP/IP:@{fg text}
               If  checked,  cdxNetLaunch  will  never  automatically  stop
               AmiTCP.  That is useful if you are using a network basing on
               AmiTCP/IP.
     @{fg shine}Never go offline:@{fg text}
               If   checked,   cdxNetLaunch  will  never  automatically  go
               offline.  You may want to use this option if you are testing
               new software or stuff.

 @{fg shine}@{b}IO window(s):@{ub}@{fg text}

     @{fg shine}@{"Define command IO...:" LINK Prefs_CmdIO}@{fg text}
               Opens  a  requester  which  allows  you to modify the output
               window  for  the  commands  cdxNetLaunch  executes  for  you
               (startnet, stopnet, online, offline).
     @{fg shine}Reports...:@{fg text}
               Opens/closes the report window.
               This won't be part of the final version.

 @{fg shine}@{b}Commodity settings:@{ub}@{fg text}

     @{fg shine}@{"Define hotkey...:" LINK Prefs_HotKey}@{fg text}
               Opens a requester which allows you to change the hotkey used
               to open the command window of cdxNetLaunch (CX_HOTKEY).
     @{fg shine}Start with window:@{fg text}
               If  checked,  cdxNetLaunch will open the command window when
               it starts up (CX_POPUP).
     @{fg shine}Disabled:@{fg text}
               If  checked,  cdxNetLaunch won't have a look for any further
               applications  that you're running.
                @{i}Note  that I  recommend  to  never use this option since it
                could bring much trouble to cdxNetLaunch !@{ui}
               Might be invoked by Exchange/Disable, too.

 @{fg shine}@{b}Configuration:@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}
 These  functions will cause unforseeable sideeffects if you have @{"manually" LINK ConfigManualLimits}
 configurated cdxNetLaunch !
 Please do not use them if you done so (@{"further information ?" LINK ConfigManualLimits}) !
@{ub}
     @{fg shine}@{"Configuration...:" LINK ConfigMainWin}@{fg text}
               Runs the configuration program of cdxNetLaunch.
               This   requester   will  even  appear  if  you  modify  your
               @{"AmiTCP:bin/startnet" LINK AmiTCP:bin/startnet/Main} script.
     @{fg shine}No online checks:@{fg text}
               This  buttons says cdxNetLaunch not to check whether you are
               online.
               This  might  be  neccessary  if  cdxNetLaunch  shows you are
               online  but you are obviously not (try re-configurating your
               serial.device, first !):  You are not online but the command
               window rejects to go online (gadget disabled).
     @{fg shine}Supervise startnet:@{fg text}
               Says  that  cdxNetLaunch  should  not automatically open the
               configuration window if you modified you AmiTCP:bin/startnet
               script.  In general, you'd modify this script to change your
               AmiTCP  configuration.   Since  it  is  very  important  for
               cdxNetLaunch  to  be  installed  correctly, you should leave
               that on.
     @{fg shine}No date checks:@{fg text}
               Normally,    cdxNetLaunch   compares   the   date   of   its
               configuration  and  of  the startnet script in order to find
               our  whether  you changed your AmiTCP configuration.  On the
               other  hand, some may not have a battery clock thus it won't
               be very useful here ;-)

 @{fg shine}Save preferences:@{fg text}
               Save all changes.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE UseAppWin "The new application window"
@TOC Usage
@PREV UseCmdWin

                        @{b}@{u}THE NEW APPLICATION WINDOW:@{ub}@{uu}

 This  window  appears if a previously unknown application is attempting to
use  AmiTCP/IP.   This  requester  will  allow  you  to define what kind of
application it is.

            +---------------------------------------------+--+
            | cdxNetLaunch: User message                  |  |
            +---------------------------------------------+--+
            |                                                |
            | Introduce new AmiTCP/IP application:           |
            |                                                |
            | ---------------------------------------------- |
            |                                                |
            |  @{fg shine}Name/ID@{fg text}: [@{i}name of new application @{ui}         ]  |
            |                                                |
            |  [x] @{fg shine}Application@{fg text}             [x] @{fg shine}TCP: device@{fg text}   |
            |  [x] @{fg shine}Go offline after connection is finished@{fg text}   |
            |                                                |
            | ---------------------------------------------- |
            |                                                |
            |            [@{fg shine}Okay@{fg text}]   [@{fg shine}Help@{fg text}]   [@{fg shine}Skip@{fg text}]            |
            |                                                |
            +------------------------------------------------+



 The  most  important  checkbox  is the @{fg shine}Application@{fg text} checkbox.  If you check
this,  it  means  that  the  program described in the @{fg shine}Name/ID@{fg text} box is not an
AmiTCP or sana2.device program.
 In  this  manner  "is an AmiTCP or sana2 program" means that it is @{i}part @{ui}of
AmiTCP  or used to control the sana2 device.  The "bootpconfig" program for
example  is  an  AmiTCP  program because it is @{i}needed @{ui}to go online.  On the
other  hand,  "ping"  or  "telnet" are not AmiTCP programs but applications
becuase they'll make use of AmiTCP and are not necessary to use AmiTCP.

                                 @{u}Gadgets:@{uu}

 @{fg shine}Name/ID:@{fg text}      This field is the (internal) name of the program that is new
               to cdxNetLaunch.

 @{fg shine}Application:@{fg text}  Checking  that  box means that the program is an application
               which is not neccessary for AmiTCP/IP or your sana2.device.
               Internally  non-application  programs  are  not  supervised.
               I.e.  the program described won't start/stop AmiTCP or force
               to go off-/online.
               Additionally,   cdxNetLaunch  expects  that  program  to  be
               unloaded when AmiTCP is been stopped.

 @{fg shine}Go offline after connection is finished:@{fg text}
               @{i}[for applications only]@{ui}
               Checking  that  box  means  that  you  want your modem to go
               offline  if  the  program did its work and doesn't need your
               modem to stay online.
               Please  note  that  programs  like  YAM  or  AWeb  will  not
               permanently  use  the  AmiTCP stack or the line.  That means
               that cdxNetLaunch can't find out whether it would be nice to
               go  offline  /  stop AmiTCP if the program closes its AmiTCP
               access.  Note that cdxNetLaunch won't go offline immediately
               but after a certain @{"time delay" LINK Prefs_Delay}.
               If you don't understand what I try to say, @{"see an example" LINK Ex_GoOffBut}.

 @{fg shine}TCP: device:@{fg text}  @{i}[for non-applications only]@{ui}
               Do  only check this button if the Name/ID field matches your
               TCP:   device.  Normally, you will define that device in the
               configuration  but  some  might  use  another  device  which
               matches  the  TCP:   device.   I  recommend  to  check  this
               checkbox  only  if the window opens with that box is already
               checked  since  cdxNetLaunch  will in most cases itself find
               out whether it is the TCP:  device or not !

 @{fg shine}Okay:@{fg text}         Accepts the upper settings and saves them (recommended).

 @{fg shine}Help:@{fg text}         This page.

 @{fg shine}Skip:@{fg text}         You  may  click at this button if you don't want to save any
               settings  for  the new program.  It will be assumed to be an
               application, then.

 Please  note  that  cdxNetLaunch  will  -  in most cases - set the correct
values  by  itself.   If  you  are  not sure about the type of the program,
please simply leave it as it is !
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Ex_GoOffBut "Example when to use 'Go offline after connection is finished"

 @{u}Example 1: AWeb doesn't like this option@{uu}

 Imagine  you  are using AWeb and you selected "Go offline after connection
is finished".
 You now start to download any web-page.

 AWeb  spawns  a  second process which opens AmiTCP (=> cdxNetLaunch starts
AmiTCP)  and  then  tries  to  establish  a  connection  to  the server (=>
cdxNetLaunch goes online).
 Now, if the page is downloaded, the AWeb sub-process closes the connection
to the server.  cdxNetLaunch now thinks that AWeb has done its job and goes
offline  and  then  stops  AmiTCP  (after  the @{"delays" LINK ConfigPrefs} defined flew by).
 You  see:  If you now click on any link on the web-page, cdxNetLaunch will
again load AmiTCP, go online etc.
 In  such a case it might be more comfortable if the line remains connected
and AmiTCP isn't needed to be loaded everytime you click at a link.
 Therefore  I'd  advise  to  un-check  the  "Go offline after connection is
finished" checkbox here.

 @{u}Example 2: telnet does like it@{uu}

 Another example is telnet: You disable the "Go offline..." option.

 You  start  telnet  (=>  AmiTCP  will  be  loaded),  get  your  connection
(=> you're  going  online)  and  play  around.  Then you logout, and telnet
closes the connection and finishes its work with AmiTCP.
 You   will   now  remain  connected  because  you  didn't  said  that  you
want to go offline automatically after the job has been done.

 In such a case it would be the best to select the "Go offline..." option !
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Prefs "The preferences requesters"
@TOC Main
@NEXT Quick
@PREV Usage

                     @{b}@{u}USING THE PREFERENCES REQUESTERS:@{ub}@{uu}

 There  are several requesters which allow you to modify certain options of
cdxNetLaunch.You can open them by choosing the matching @{"menu item" LINK UseCmdWin 35} from the
command window.

 @{u}Standard settings:@{uu}

  @{" Function delays          " LINK Prefs_Delay}
  @{" Command IO window        " LINK Prefs_CmdIO}
  @{" Commodity hotkey         " LINK Prefs_hotkey}

 @{u}Configurationą:@{uu}

  @{" Configurate cdxNetLaunch " LINK ConfigMainWin}

 ą:  I guess that - if you once configured cdxNetLaunch - you won't need to
make use of these stuff anymore ;^>
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Prefs_Delay "Define function delays..."
@TOC Prefs
@NEXT Prefs_CmdIO
@PREV

                          @{b}@{u}DEFINE FUNCTION DELAYS:@{ub}@{uu}

 This  requester  will appear if you select @{i}Adjust time delays...@{ui}  from the
@{i}Preferences/Automatic Operations @{ui}@{"menu" LINK UseCmdWin}.

            +-+-----------------------------------------+--+--+
            | | cdxNetLaunch: Adjust timer delays       |  |  |
            +-+-----------------------------------------+--+--+
            |                                                 |
            | Auto close AmiTCP after...       |  [  @{fg shine}Undo@{fg text}  ]  |
            |                                  |  [  @{fg shine}Help@{fg text}  ]  |
            | A: [@{fg shine}········«O»········@{fg text}]  0 min  |              |
            | B: [@{fg shine}········«O»········@{fg text}] 20 sec  |              |
            |    [x] @{fg shine}Never@{fg text}                     |              |
            |                                  |              |
            | ---------------------------------+              |
            |                                  |              |
            | Auto go offline after...         |              |
            |                                  |              |
            | D: [@{fg shine}········«O»········@{fg text}]  0 min  |  [  @{fg shine}Okay@{fg text}  ]  |
            | E: [@{fg shine}········«O»········@{fg text}] 20 sec  |  [ @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text} ]  |
            |    [x] @{fg shine}Never@{fg text}                     |              |
            |                                                 |
            +-------------------------------------------------+

 @{b}@{fg shine}Auto close AmiTCP after...:@{fg text}@{ub}
   @{fg shine}Scrollbars (min/sec):@{fg text}
               Use  these  two  bars  to  edit  the  delay  for the @{b}stopnet@{ub}
               command:
               If  cdxNetLaunch  recognizes that the last application which
               used AmiTCP/IP has finished its work, cdxNetLaunch will wait
               this time delay before it will really quit AmiTCP/IP.
               This  is  included because it is very silly if you quit one
               network related program and start another afterwards.  With-
               out  this  delay  time,  between  this stop first/start next
               AmiTCP would be stopped and immediately run again.
               @{i}The minimum value is 1 second.@{ui}
   @{fg shine}Never:@{fg text}
               If  you  check  this,  cdxNetLaunch will never automatically
               stop AmiTCP.

 @{b}@{fg shine}Auto go offline after...:@{fg text}@{ub}
   @{fg shine}Scrollbars (min/sec):@{fg text}
               Use  these  two  bars  to  edit  the  delay  for the @{b}offline@{ub}
               command:
               If  cdxNetLaunch  recognizes that the last application which
               needed  you  to  be  connected  has finished its connection,
               cdxNetLaunch will wait this time delay before it will really
               goes offline.
               This  feature  is been added because some programs like AWeb
               don't  permanently  use  the line, but do much accesses from
               different  processes:   You  load  a  WWW-page.  The page is
               ready,  but  now AWeb starts to load the pictures.  If there
               isn't  any time delay, cdxNetLaunch would go offline between
               the end of the transmission of the page and the start of the
               transmission of the picture(s).
               Try it, if you don't know what I'm talking off ;')
               @{i}The minimum value is 1 second.@{ui}
   @{fg shine}Never:@{fg text}
               If  you check this, cdxNetLaunch will never automatically go
               offline.

 @{fg shine}Undo:@{fg text}         Restore your old values.

 @{fg shine}Help:@{fg text}         This page

 @{fg shine}Okay:@{fg text}         Accept the new values.
               Remember to select the @{i}Preferences/Save preferences @{ui}from the
               @{"command window" LINK UseCmdWin} menu to save your changes !

 @{fg shine}Cancel:@{fg text}       Cancel ;-)

 @{fg shine}CLOSE GADGET:@{fg text} Same as @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Prefs_CmdIO "Define output window for function commands..."
@TOC Prefs
@NEXT Prefs_HotKey
@PREV Prefs_Delay

                           @{b}@{u}DEFINE OUTPUT WINDOW:@{ub}@{uu}
 This  requester  will  appear if you select @{i}Define command IO...@{ui}  from the
@{i}Preferences/IO window(s) @{ui}@{"menu" LINK UseCmdWin}.

            +-+-----------------------------------------+--+--+
            | | cdxNetLaunch: Command I/O window        |  |  |
            +-+-----------------------------------------+--+--+
            |                                                 |
            | Send system output to:                          |
            |                                                 |
            |  @{fg shine}Stream@{fg text}: [.abcdefg....................] [@{fg shine}Test@{fg text}]  |
            |                                                 |
            | ----------------------------------------------- |
            |                                                 |
            |   [  @{fg shine}Okay@{fg text}  ] [  @{fg shine}Undo@{fg text}  ] [  @{fg shine}Help@{fg text}  ] [ @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text} ]   |
            |                                                 |
            +-------------------------------------------------+

 @{fg shine}Stream:@{fg text}       This is the output stream definition where cdxNetLaunch will
               send the output from the @{"scripts" LINK Scripts} to.
               This  stream  will  be  opened  as an old file, therefore it
               isn't possible to use a @{i}file@{ui} here.
               Use    any    window    definition    (CON:x/y/wid/hi/title/
               AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT etc.) or a NIL:  entry for @{u}no@{uu} output.

 @{fg shine}Test:@{fg text}         Using  this button you can test whether cdxNetLaunch is able
               to open your stream or not.

 @{fg shine}Okay:@{fg text}         Accept the new values.
               Remember to select the @{i}Preferences/Save preferences @{ui}from the
               @{"command window" LINK UseCmdWin} menu to save your changes !

 @{fg shine}Undo:@{fg text}         Restore your old values.

 @{fg shine}Help:@{fg text}         This page

 @{fg shine}Cancel:@{fg text}       Cancel ;-)

 @{fg shine}CLOSE GADGET:@{fg text} Same as @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}.
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Prefs_HotKey "Define hotkey to open command window..."
@TOC Prefs
@NEXT Prefs_Scripts
@PREV Prefs_CmdIO

                            @{b}@{u}DEFINE NEW HOTKEY:@{ub}@{uu}

 This  requester  will  appear  if  you  select  @{i}Define hotkey...@{ui}  from the
@{i}Preferences/Commodity settings @{ui}@{"menu" LINK UseCmdWin}.

            +-+-----------------------------------------+--+--+
            | | cdxNetLaunch: Command I/O window        |  |  |
            +-+-----------------------------------------+--+--+
            |                                                 |
            | Open/close command window by:                   |
            |                                                 |
