@remark -----------------------------------------------------------
@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Info_Sana2 "What's a sana2.device ?"

 @{u}sana2.device@{uu}

 A  sana2.device  is  a  "program" which can establish connections to other
computers via a local net or via the telephone line (modem).
 A  sana2.device  related  to  cdxNetLaunch is always a device that you are
normally  using  to  establish  a  connection  to another computer (i.e.  a
provider).
 I myself  prefer the @{"ppp.device ©1994,1995 Holger Kruse" LINK Info_ppp} which will make a
ppp  connection  to  your  internet provider, but you may choose any device
you like. There are several sana2.devices available in the aminet.

 Normally, you would store such a device in @{i}DEVS:networks/ @{ui}!
@ENDNODE

@remark -----------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Info_CxKeys "Commodity.library hotkeys"

                          @{b}@{u}HOW TO DEFINE A HOTKEY:@{ub}@{uu}

 A  hotkey  is  a sequence of several keys which leads into any reaction by
your computer i.e. a program which controls this key.
 Amiga hotkeys are now - since Version 2.0 of the AmigaOS - expressed using
a standardized notation.

 A  hotkey-definition  always  consists  of  @{u}one@{uu}  @{i}normal @{ui} key  and  @{u}several@{uu}
@{i}qualifiers@{ui}.

 @{i}Normal @{ui}keys are for example: a,b,c,d,e,f...,!,?,ą,
                              F1,F2,ESC,RETURN,SPACE,
                              UP,DOWN,HELP,TAB etc.
                              @{i}(every printable key)@{ui}

 @{i}Qualifiers@{ui} are:              shift, lshiftą, rshiftą,
                              alt, lalt, ralt,
                              control, ctrl,
                              lamiga, ramiga,
                              capslock

 (ą=shift stands for both (one of the two shift keys), rshift for the right
key and lshift for the left one).
   
 If  you  now want to define a hotkey string, you can mix up the @{i}qualifiers@{ui}
and add @{u}one@{uu} of the @{i}normal @{ui}keys.

 Examples:

      lshift r
      lalt rshift x
      lalt X                  [note that this means lalt+shift+x]
      ctrl ESC

 Invalid examples:

      lshift                  [no normal key]
      ctrl x a                [more than one normal key]
      ctrl x shift            [qualifier past normal key]
@ENDNODE

